y.\nLastly, we present some potential use cases of the dataset. We expect this\ndataset will be a valuable resource and serve as a starting point to fight\nproliferation of fake news in low resource languages.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 23 Feb 2021 16:47:41 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-02-24"}
{"id":"2102.11768","submitter":"Gideon Amir","authors":"Gideon Amir, Itai Arieli, Galit Ashkenazi-Golan and Ron Peretz","title":"Robust Naive Learning in Social Networks","comments":"27 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.PR cs.DM cs.SI physics.soc-ph","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  We study a model of opinion exchange in social networks where a state of the\nworld is realized and every agent receives a zero-mean noisy signal of the\nrealized state. It is known from Golub and Jackson that under the DeGroot\ndynamics agents reach a consensus which is close to the state of the world when\nthe network is large. The DeGroot dynamics, however, is highly non-robust and\nthe presence of a single `bot' that does not adhere to the updating rule, can\nsway the public consensus to any other value. We introduce a variant of the\nDeGroot dynamics which we call \\emph{ $\\varepsilon$-DeGroot}. The\n$\\varepsilon$-DeGroot dynamics approximates the standard DeGroot dynamics and\nlike the DeGroot dynamics it is Markovian and stationary. We show that in\ncontrast to the standard DeGroot dynamics, the $\\varepsilon$-DeGroot dynamics\nis highly robust both to the presence of bots and to certain types of\nmisspecifications.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 23 Feb 2021 16:00:35 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-02-24"}
